Public procurement of works and corruption prevention
Joint report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and Overview
The award of services by public authorities is of great importance both for the state and for the economy.
The task of the state is to use public funds as economically and sparingly as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by public authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure that competition is largely unrestricted across borders, contracting authorities must comply with EU requirements when awarding contracts above certain value limits (threshold values).
To this end, the EU Member States have to transpose and apply the EU's public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The award of services is also an area at risk of corruption.
Because of the inherently high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore implement appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue favouritism in the award of their contracts.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to carry out parallel audits for the EU-wide award of construction services as well as for the prevention of corruption.
The tests focused on the application of the EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national regulations, as well as on the prevention of corruption in the award of construction works in civil engineering, road construction and transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU thresholds have also been taken into account with regard to corruption prevention.
The audit results of both courts of auditors are summarised in this joint report.
The report is also aimed at international institutions, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
The evaluations of the Bundesrechnungshof on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional tests, which it carried out in the years 2011/2012 with the building authorities, which are responsible for the road construction and the building of the federal government in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and large-scale construction projects.
In addition, the Federal Audit Office drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on audit findings from 2008 to 2011, which included construction work in road construction, railway track construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the awarding of federal public contracts is carried out primarily by the building authorities of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for awarding contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.
In the construction sector, the awarding of contracts is carried out on a decentralised basis by those bodies that use state budget resources.
In both countries, freelancers are also employed for part of the procurement procedures.
When juxtaposing the evaluations, differences in the procurement law and the market structure for construction services of both countries must be taken into account.
Development of public procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures, limited to the national sphere, are governed by budgetary law and the administrative provisions based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national procurement, many complementary individual schemes are provided by internal administrative provisions,
Such as the so-called "procurement manuals" of the Federal Government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or further formulated in compliance with the law on the award of contracts.
In the Czech Republic, the award procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and other statutory provisions, which apply both above and below the EU thresholds.
The public procurement law was substantially amended in 2012.
The new rules increased transparency in the use of public funds, allowed for greater competition and limited opportunities for corruption in the award procedure.
Principles of public procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiated procedure are particularly applicable for EU-wide awards.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are subject to national tenders (public tenders, restricted tenders, hands-free contracts) which, however, largely correspond to these EU-wide tenders.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the priority of the open procedure (for contracts to be awarded throughout the EU) and the public tender (for national contracts).
In the open procedure and in the public tender, any interested company can make an offer.
Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises.
For this purpose, the division of an overall construction measure into experts and non-participants serves above all.
The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the aforementioned features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
In Germany, there are more than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.
One exception is the simplified procedure, which allows a less stringent procedure to be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law, in line with EU law, provides for contracts to be concluded when competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
Current legislation in the Czech Republic allows contracting authorities to choose between open and non-open procedures.
There are more than 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including about 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.
