Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have conducted parallel audits in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and on the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of the two courts of auditors compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of building construction and road construction.
In doing so, they found, in essence:
The EU directives on the award of works by public authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (Nos. 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, corruption prevention is also served by the procurement regulations of both countries, which differ in their focus and detail (No. 3.2).
In both countries, an essential requirement of the procurement documents is that they must contain all the information necessary for the proper preparation of tenders.
The specifications must be neutral and must not be subject to anti-absorbing requirements.
In Germany, the procurement documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the subject of the contract sufficiently.
In Germany, construction works must be divided into lots, if possible, in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement has been largely implemented in Germany.
In its audits, particularly in the field of road construction, NKÚ found that the award of large-scale services without lots or with only very large lots could affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.
Narrowing the market potential can lead to significant cost increases and risk of price or other collusion.
According to the provisions of both countries, the contracting authorities may, under certain conditions, agree in principle with the companies already contracted additional or modified services which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).
The respective requirements for determining the type of award were mostly followed in both countries.
According to the rules of the Czech Republic, the contracting authorities are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure for EU-wide tenders or the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national tenders, applies.
This will allow more companies to make offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes it difficult to negotiate prices between bidders and leads to the most economic results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited construction authorities generally awarded the construction services throughout Europe.
Accurately estimating the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.
In Germany, cost data bases are used for the cost investigations of public buildings, in particular in the construction sector,
Which are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective tool (No. 4.2).
In the case of construction works to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and announcements have to be published, which is intended to strengthen competition by allowing interested companies to prepare for the planned awards at an early stage.
As a rule, the approved building authorities complied with this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may have affected competition (No. 4.3).
The selection of candidates for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be announced beforehand.
In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting authorities in both countries are to switch as frequently as possible among the companies to be invited when selecting candidates.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are some very detailed requirements in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations did not take these requirements into account.
In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).
In both countries, it is in the interest of fair competition to ensure that companies interested in making a bid receive the same information during the bidding phase.
Contact between these companies and freelancers involved in the production of the service description is to be avoided as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The approved building authorities in Germany, however, did not comply with these requirements in part (No. 4.5).
The opening of tenders in both countries must take into account, in particular, the principle of multi-eyes and the principle of transparency.
The provisions on labelling, documentation, custody and confidentiality of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.
The tests in both countries revealed only a few complaints (No. 4.6).
In both countries, the examination and evaluation of the offers are determined by guidelines for the organisation of the structure and the sequence of events.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
For example, contracting authorities handed over bids for examination to third parties without first seeing through the bids and adequately documenting anomalies.
The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).
At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition will be informed of the intended appointment prior to the award of the contract.
This possibility of legal protection also has a preventive function against corruptive behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for the possibility of judicial review for non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities fail to comply with the deadlines set for the award of the contract or deviate from the bidders" offer in terms of content (No. 4.8).
The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible in the case of the audited construction authorities in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the award notices of some procedures.
Some of the shortcomings identified also reduced the corruption-preventing function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).
Fundamentals of EU public procurement law and corruption prevention
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the procurement coordination and appeal directives, which had to be transposed into national law by the Member States.
The European Union's general principles of awarding contracts are, in particular, that of competition, equal treatment or non-discrimination, and that of transparency.
In order to achieve these objectives, the procurement coordination directive sets out specific rules for construction works to be awarded throughout the EU.
In order to do this, their estimated order totals must reach or exceed 5,000,000 euros at present.
The regulations concern in particular the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, including for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualification of the applicants and the Remedies Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of the applicants and bidders.
In the event of possible infringements of public procurement law, the companies concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.
Corruption prevention
The importance of corruption prevention
In both countries, there is no legal definition of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private gain,
Which is usually caused by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
According to estimates, the global cost of corruption is 5% of global economic output.
For the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.
In doing so, they have to review the organisation of their administrative structures and procedures in areas that are particularly vulnerable to corruption, in order to make appropriate safeguards against corruption there.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corruptive abuse.
The award of public works is generally regarded as an area of work that is particularly vulnerable to corruption.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery, as well as the acceptance and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on the prevention of corruption12 in the Federal Administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following principles must be observed in the award area: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eye principle and transparency, basic separation of planning, award and accounting, precise and complete documentation of the procurement procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the procurement legislation.
In 2011, the competent Federal Ministry for Public Procurement in the area of federal highways introduced an electronically supported control system,
With the award data - such as estimated costs and contract amounts - as well as information on the freelancers involved, it is collected across the board and evaluated for anomalies.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders, as well as the prohibition of any discrimination, are the most important bases for preventing corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on the fight against corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended in it have already been incorporated into national public procurement law and related administrative provisions by 14.
The main provisions of the new legislation are: lowering the thresholds for smaller contracts, requiring the contracting authority to notify the tenders in advance, including naming the reasons for the tender, prohibiting the limitation of the number of tenderers in open procedures and thus eliminating the possibility of selecting tenders by means of lottery procedures, introducing the obligation to publish the contract documents and all the annexes, introducing the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Results of the examination of the various stages of the award procedure
Award documents
Procurement Documents The procurement documents must contain all the information that the bidders need in order to make an appropriate offer.
In particular, the award documents must allow for an accurate calculation.
Bidders must not be given risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The award documents consist in particular of the description of the service and the terms of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proof of the qualification (ownership) of the bidders as well as the criteria, which are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
The requirements of EU law for the procurement documents are addressed in particular to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.
The service description must, in principle, be product-neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only allowed under strict conditions.
The avoidance of anti-competitive provisions in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of corruption prevention.
In addition, unclear or inaccurate information in the award documents must be avoided, as it opens up scope for speculation in the creation of the tenders and for manipulation of their valuation.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
Identical or similar regulations In both countries, the EU legal requirements for the technical specifications have been transposed into national law.
In principle, the services are to be tendered in a product-neutral manner without factory specifications.
In the service descriptions, the individual services must, as a rule, be subdivided into performance units with respective quantities.
The prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g., euros per m2 or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can benefits be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the service descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include services that do not determine whether they are needed.
Compensation according to flat rates or according to time expenditure must be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on indefinite requirements in the award documents.
The service descriptions must enable bidders to prepare their bids safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The call for tenders will not be made public until the tender documents have been completed.
Diverging rules
There is no obligation to tender for construction works in lots in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be carried out, the public contracting authorities can subdivide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are to be divided into lots, separately according to the quantity (individual) and/or type or subject (individual).
The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, to expand the number of possible suppliers and to make it more difficult to agree prices.
This type of award is generally considered to be the most economical.
In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be specified in the award documents, both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
The aim is for the applicants to be fully and conclusively aware of the criteria according to which their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only mandatory in EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the assessment criteria are only to be recorded in an administrative award notice.
Procurement documents, which are drawn up by commissioned freelancers, may not contain references to these offices or involved planners or surveyors in Germany with the building construction and some road construction administrations.
This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the client's knowledge of the contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send out tender documents or to interpret planning documents for inspection.
Only the client is the contact person of the companies.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic on this.
Additional or modified services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (subsidies), almost always apply to large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of supplements to the company already contracted, without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of the supplementary performance may not exceed half of the main contract.
In addition, the additional services cannot be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to such an award without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already under way.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the already contracted company, under the regulations in Germany, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is in principle not possible.
The determination of the remuneration for the additional services is based on the agreed prices and on the basis of the price determination of the already issued order.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, minimum quantities cannot be charged with additional supplementary performance.
Key findings of the audit
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral tender
In individual cases, the specifications contained references to national technical approvals or standards, which had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.
Some performance descriptions also contained product-related specifications - for example, for graffiti protection, joint tapes or noise protection plates - without this being necessary.
In some cases, performance requirements were described so precisely that only one product was eligible.
List of services subdivided by sub-services
In none of the cases examined, the BRH has found violations of the requirement to tender services in principle in a list of services subdivided according to partial services.
Completeness of the service descriptions
In the vast majority of cases, the tender documents were completed before the tenders began.
In some cases, the tender documents had to be corrected during the tender phase, as some positions or deadlines had changed.
In some cases, the performance lists contained positions where it was not determined whether they were needed.
A list of services for demolition work even consisted of almost half of such requirements.
Loose and scoring criteria
In the case of many contracts, there was no prescribed justification for the fact that the services, which were mainly advertised according to experts, were not further divided into partial ones.
There were no objections to the indication of the criteria to be used in the evaluation of the offers.
References to freelancers
A small part of the performance descriptions contained references to the freelancers involved.
Their names were partly on the cover sheets or in attached plans or reports.
In one case, the contracting authority even explicitly asked the applicants to contact the architect "on questions of the tender."
In the construction sector in particular, the contracting authorities attributed the above-mentioned complaints mainly to the omissions of the freelancers responsible for drawing up the specifications of services.
The construction services pointed out the lack of capacity in order to be able to adequately control the performance descriptions.
NKÚ
Technical specifications and product-neutral tender In the public procurement for the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units, a supplier and a specific product brand were specified in the service description.
The contracting authority did not allow the use of comparable products without justifying this.
Suppliers and products were also specified in the tender for the construction of several university buildings.
Performance descriptions with performance units
In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the contracting authority did not clearly specify the scope and type of services required in the specifications.
As performance units, it merely indicated the converted space of the individual buildings in cubic metres.
Completeness of the service descriptions
During the construction of a motorway bypass, the service descriptions were changed four times during the period August to September 2009 as part of a non-open procedure,
As the range of services had increased considerably and the technical requirements had changed.
Tender documents for social buildings included inaccurate location information, inadequate structural preliminary examinations and incomplete design drawings, requiring additional services to be contracted.
When building a large library building, the performance description of the interior did not include product quality requirements.
As a result of this lack of specifications, some sub-contractors built up overpriced and unreasonably high-quality equipment.
Loose and eligibility criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of works into partial lots or the award of partial contracts is not mandatory.
An examination of the three major sections of the construction of a motorway ring showed that if selected parts were allocated in a way, savings of up to 31.6 million euros would have been possible, with a total cost of 620.3 million euros.
For example, in the case of six different buildings, which were the subject of a single contract, 2.5 million euros (25%) could have been saved in the event of a voluntary award.
If the construction of 20 bridges were to be dismissed, savings of EUR 11.5 million (25%) would have been possible compared to a total award.
In the award of construction services in road construction, the central contracting authority submitted very extensive reference requirements as eligibility criteria.
In the construction of part of a motorway, the contracting authority required bidders, in an open procedure, to prove, among other things, at least three road construction projects carried out, each worth 28 million euros from the last five years.
In the Czech Republic, a maximum of nine suppliers met these requirements.
The public award of another part of a motorway included six separate construction projects, in which the contracting authority had set an annual construction volume of at least EUR 480 million over the last three years as a qualifying criterion for the companies.
Two-thirds of the funds raised for road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (i.e. 2.5 billion euros out of a total of 3.7 billion euros) were contracted by a total of five companies that carried out the contracts alone or as a working group.
In 46 procurement procedures with an order volume of 528 million euros, only two or even only one bidder made an offer.
The NKÚ pointed out that a narrowing of the market potential could lead to significant cost increases.
Additional services
In the case of the construction of a motorway bypass, the contracting authority did not apply any of the legal procedures for the award of additional services in two cases, nor did it enter into any written contracts for the additional services.
Due to unclear quantity and quality requirements, the first case yielded up to 63.7 million euros (net) and in the second case up to 165.4 million euros (net), which increased the respective order volume by 21% and 91% respectively.
