Other findings
On the basis of a sample test of construction projects, the NKÚ found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway kilometre in the Czech Republic is up to 14.6 million euros.
In Deuschland, on the other hand, the average cost of a four-lane motorway kilometre is up to 10.4 million euros, according to an evaluation of long-term data from the Federal Ministry of Buildings.
This comparison suggests that motorway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take into account EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for a sufficient degree of certainty in the performance descriptions should enable bidders to calculate and draw up their bids in an appropriate manner,
Protect the client from additional services to be agreed at a later date and also limit the scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for the award documents are supplemented by regulations aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and the possibility of manipulation.
In the Czech Republic, there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency is increased by publishing the evaluation criteria in the non-EU procurement procedures.
The requirements for the description of services have been largely met in both countries.
In some cases, however, it was necessary to object to deviations that may have led to restrictions on competition.
The requirement for the formation of lots in Germany promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of the NKÚ, the award of extensive services without lots or with only very large lots may result in restrictions of the field of suppliers to only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements for road construction in the Czech Republic have meant that public contracts are awarded only to a narrow circle of suppliers and that smaller and medium-sized enterprises are not allowed to compete.
Also, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other collusion.
When awarding and remunerating additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches differ in both countries.
According to the EU requirements and the German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded without a public procurement procedure under certain conditions.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20%, up to which additional services can be awarded without notice to the original contractor in the negotiated procedure.
