This limit is often exceeded,
As the scope of services for public contracts is often insufficiently defined.
If the excess is greater than 20%, the additional benefits must be advertised with public notice.
By splitting services into lots, restrictions on competition and the resulting adverse consequences can be avoided.
Defining the method of awarding and taking into account the EU threshold value
By determining the type of award, the client determines the extent of the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential applicants and bidders largely unfettered, for example, through the choice of an open procedure, or limit it by imposing non-public procurement procedures.
For construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, Europe-wide procurement procedures must be applied.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In choosing the type of award, the contracting authority must take into account, in particular, the European rules on competition and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of the construction work of a project is at or above the current EU threshold of 5,000,000 euros, the construction work is generally to be awarded Europe-wide according to open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
In the case of construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold, the contracting authority may derogate to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European procurement and award works in national procurement contracts, provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than 1,000,000 euros and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total contract value of all construction contracts.
A single construction project must not be divided into individual measures without a compelling reason, or deliberately valued at too low a cost, in order to remove the obligation to award construction services on an Europe-wide basis.
As restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the type of award plays a major role in preventing corruption.
The detailed justification of the chosen type of award as well as the examination of the application of the EU procurement rules are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed the EU rules on procurement procedures and the threshold into national law.
Diverging rules
The Czech Republic has also transferred the basic equality of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU directive to its construction contracts, which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the non-open procedure, without having to justify or justify the decision. Other procedures, however, are only possible under certain conditions defined by law.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or, in the case of national contracts, the public tender is in principle a priority. This is determined by budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the directives on the prevention of corruption.
Other types of award - as well as the non-open procedure or the restricted tender - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated in the public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be justified and documented in a comprehensible manner.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or the public tender is intended to ensure that competition is as unrestricted as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by fixing it on certain bidders and to make it more difficult for bidders to agree on prices.
The principle of public tendering is a central element of corruption prevention in Germany.
Accurately estimating the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of award.
The construction services in Germany can use planning and cost databases of public administrations as well as other organisations to determine the likely costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost characteristics for building categories, use units, components or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost parameters, the expected contract value of a planned project or construction work to be awarded can be determined.
Corresponding cost databases for road construction have only a few building authorities in Germany.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road construction authorities is planned.
Contracting authorities in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price determinations of comparable construction measures to determine the likely cost of construction services.
In most cases, the cost assessments are based on estimates of the funding body or are based on the amount of funds made available to the construction department.
Measures to standardise cost-assessment procedures are still in the early stages.
Within the framework of the anti-corruption plan for 2011 - 2012, the relevant ministries were commissioned to create a database for standardised building materials and materials.
