Key findings of the audit BRH
Selection of the award procedure
The audited contracting authorities largely wrote out the construction works in open proceedings or in public tenders, thereby complying with the budgetary and public procurement regulations.
In 2011, 59.5% of the federal building services in the construction sector were advertised either publicly or in open proceedings.
In road construction, this figure was 94.8%.
In the selection of non-public tenders, there were sometimes no detailed reasons why the contracting authorities had to deviate from the principle of open procedure or public tender.
In a cross-sectional investigation, the BRH found, on the basis of more than 16,000 procurement procedures, that non-public tenders have significant competitive disadvantages compared to open procedures and public tenders, and increase the risk of manipulation and corruption.
In the construction sector, more than twice as many bids were submitted for public tenders as for restricted tenders and almost three times as many bids as for hands-free tenders.
The investigation also showed that bid prices for restricted tenders and open-handed tenders were on average 6% and 10% higher than for public tenders.
Parallel studies by the Federal Ministry of Building and a National Audit Office confirmed the differences in economic efficiency between public and non-public tenders.
As a result of its studies on economic efficiency, the Federal Ministry of Buildings even found twice as many differences between public and non-public procurement procedures.
Taking into account the EU threshold value
In the case of the construction projects for which they had calculated an expected total contract amount of more than 5,000,000 euros, the audited contracting authorities usually drew up procurement plans in which they determined the construction works to be awarded according to EU-wide as well as the construction works to be awarded according to national procurement procedures.
According to the procurement plans, this meant that a share of more than 80% of construction work was to be awarded across the EU.
It could not be established that the obligation to award EU-wide contracts was being circumvented by cost estimates that were too low.
However, it was partly due to incorrect calculations that the minimum percentage of EU-wide procurement procedures actually fell short.
During construction, some contracting authorities improperly changed the provisions of their procurement plans.
They did not justify these changes and did not demonstrate that the minimum percentage of EU-wide procurement procedures continued to be respected.
For most of the construction measures examined, the proportion of EU-wide contracts was generally lower according to the accounting results than provided for under the procurement plan.
In some cases, for construction projects above the EU threshold, the contracting authorities breached the requirement to tender all 1,000,000 euros and more large individual lots in EU-wide procedures,
And chose national procedures instead.
