Choice of award method
In the case of several major construction projects, such as the construction of some sections of the motorway, construction projects in the context of a major sporting event and housing projects, the contracting authorities divided works into several sub-contracts, although these services were similar or comparable.
As a result of these distributions, the individual benefits were no longer above the threshold and were then awarded in simplified procedures or even in breach of legal requirements.
Calculation methods for the estimated order value
In road construction, the existing price databases for this area were an inadequate tool for determining the expected order values.
The data were based on just completed construction projects, but there was evidence of a lack of economic efficiency, unnecessary additional effort or excessive profits of the contractors.
For three sections of a motorway ring, actual prices were about 37% lower than expected order values determined with the help of the database.
In the meantime, the Ministry of Transport revised the databases in order to be able to take into account not only the supply prices of recent years, but also comparable market prices and price increase indices in the construction sector.
In the construction sector, the expected order values were based on the cost values estimated by the project architects or on the estimates of the investors.
The actual order values differed greatly from the estimates.
The estimated price for the conversion or expansion of a large library was twice as high as the contract value agreed later on, however, eight supplements in the course of construction led to an increase in costs of 2.1 million euros and 27%, respectively.
Similarly, the actual contract value for the construction of a library depot was 33% lower than the estimated price, with cost increases in the construction phase.
In other cases, supply prices exceeded estimates and increased during construction.
In the case of the construction of a large library, the estimated price was exceeded by 16 million euros, or 22%; in the case of the construction of a judicial building, the costs increased disproportionately by 139%, as the area of use had only increased by 12%.
