Both countries have transposed the EU regulations for determining the type of award and taking into account the EU threshold value into national law, so the respective regulations are largely in line with each other.
However, the priority of the open procedure or public tender in Germany goes beyond the EU requirements and the regulations in force in the Czech Republic.
Compared to the non-public procurement procedures, more companies have the opportunity to compete in public or public tenders.
The public procurement procedures lead to a higher number of offers and to the most economical results.
The risk of corruption will be considerably improved by not limiting the field of candidates by the client's manipulation-prone stipulations and by making it more difficult for bidders to agree on prices.
The investigations have confirmed the advantage of the priority of the open procedure or the public tender in Germany.
Under Czech legislation, contracting authorities can award contracts through open or non-open procedures.
According to the latest changes in public procurement law, the number of bidders may no longer be limited in cases involving previous competition.
This means that the non-open procedure is now very similar to the open procedure.
In Germany, the contracting authorities have largely complied with the requirements for the priority of the open procedure or the public tender. In the Czech Republic, some services have been improperly distributed in order to circumvent the requirements for the choice of the type of award.
When taking into account the EU threshold value, errors had to be found in Germany, which led to a fall in the minimum share of tendered services across the EU.
In the Czech Republic, there is still no satisfactory solution to accurately determine the expected costs of construction and construction projects.
