In it, he has to make known, among other things, the scope of services, the process and execution dates, the special requirements as well as the evaluation criteria and their weighting.
When describing the subject of the order, the Europe-wide standardised vocabulary of the Common Procurement Vocabulary (CPV codes) must be used.
Preliminary information and notices will be published in the Official Journal of the European Union and in the procurement profile of the client.
In order to prevent discrimination against foreign applicants, announcements at national level may not contain any additional information and may only be issued after the text of the notice has been sent to the Office for Official Publications of the European Union.
Incomplete or inaccurate information in the notice may affect competition and may even encourage manipulation.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed the EU's pre-information and notice requirements into national law.
Diverging rules
In the Czech Republic, preliminary information and announcements must also be published in the case of construction works that are not to be awarded Europe-wide.
Procurement procedures may start at the earliest one month after the dispatch of the preliminary information to the EU Official Journal (for EU-wide contracts) or to the national Official Journal (for all contracts).
Only in exceptional cases can the publication of a preliminary information be dispensed with.
In Germany, no prior information is required in the non-EU procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, notices for public tenders and participation competitions before restricted tenders must be published on the Federal Internet portal and, if necessary, also in newspapers or magazines.
In the case of restricted tenders without competition, announcements of services to be awarded starting from 25,000 euros are required (ex-ante transparency).
All the planned lots of the construction projects must be listed in the preliminary information.
In Germany, this is of particular importance because of the small part of the loose construction contracts.
In the Czech Republic, the impact of this scheme is limited, as much less construction work is divided into lots.
