Selection of candidates for non-public contracts
Unlike the public procurement procedures, the non-public procurement procedures do not allow any company interested in the performance of the services to be awarded to participate in the competition.
In the case of non-public procurement procedures, the contracting authority has to make a selection in advance of which companies are to be invited to submit bids.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption The EU rules allow a limit on the number of candidates in EU-wide non-public procurement procedures.
However, in the case of open procedures, at least five companies are required to submit bids.
At least three companies must be invited to participate in negotiation procedures with the award notice.
In any case, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not lead to discrimination and must be announced beforehand.
The selection of companies to be requested is a process within the award procedure, which is highly vulnerable to manipulation, for example, by allowing certain companies to be given preferential treatment on an one-sided basis.
In addition, limiting competition to a few companies also favours possible collusion by the applicants.
In both cases, the procurement result can be significantly affected at the expense of the client.
The contracting authorities must therefore take special precautions against possible manipulation, carry out adequate checks and, in particular, ensure the transparency and comprehensibility of this procedural step.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The rules governing the selection of candidates are similar in both countries.
In addition to the EU requirements, the contracting authorities should change as frequently as possible among the companies to be requested when selecting candidates.
Nor should competition be limited to companies based in certain regions.
The contracting authorities have to justify the selection of candidates and document the process of the selection procedure in their award notes.
Diverging rules
In Germany, at least three suitable candidates are required to submit bids in the case of restricted tenders and, in principle, several in the case of open-handed tenders.
Under the new Czech rules, with the exception of two specific areas, it is not permitted to limit the number of bidders in the case of non-open procedures and negotiation procedures.
In Germany, the multi-eye principle must be observed when selecting companies.
For example, if an employee has proposed a number of companies for a non-public procurement procedure, the management level of the construction department or an agent from the contracting authority must, as a rule, amend this proposal by, for example, taking out a proposed company and/or adding a new company.
The aim is to prevent a single person from being able to conclusively determine the circle of companies to be involved in the competition.
Otherwise, in the case of manipulative intentions, this could allow for far-reaching collusion between the parties involved.
The list of companies to be requested must be treated confidentially, including with regard to freelancers, and must not be made accessible to the general public.
