Key findings of the audit
BRH
Number of applicants
The requirement to require a minimum number of companies to submit bids for non-public contracts has been met, with a few exceptions.
An evaluation of the BRH of almost 7,000 non-European procurement contracts for construction services in the construction sector showed that the contracting authorities asked an average of 6.6 companies to submit bids for restricted federal tenders in Germany and an average of 4.4 companies for hands-free tenders.
Change of companies and regional restrictions
Especially in the case of trades with few suppliers, the contracting authorities did not always change the number of selected applicants.
They took into account, in particular, companies already known to them and, in their view, tried and tested.
The reason for this was that, in the case of non-public proceedings, they had to ensure the suitability of the companies invited to compete even before the invitation to tender.
The BRH did not find an undue restriction on regional bidders in the non-public procurement procedures, but it did find a higher proportion of regionally based companies than in public tenders.
The contracting authorities mainly attributed this to the fact that, on average, the scope of services for non-public procurement is much lower and therefore, for example, longer routes are more important than for public tenders.
Multi-eyes principle and proposals freelance tigers
Contrary to the rules, the contracting authorities mostly failed to have the proposed list of requesting companies amended by an independent person.
They justified this in particular by the lack of processing capacity, deadline pressure or insufficient knowledge of alternative suitable companies.
It was also often undocumented who proposed the companies invited to submit bids.
A number of samples showed that freelancers had drawn up the list of candidates and that these proposals had been accepted unchanged by the contracting authorities.
As a result, the contracting authorities did not protect themselves to the extent necessary from possible manipulation.
Confidential treatment of the lists of bidders
At a contracting authority, the lists of companies to be requested were recorded in a data processing system that could be viewed by all employees of that service.
In the case of manipulative intentions, the names of the intended or authorised companies could have been passed on without authorisation and could, for example, allow collusion between these companies.
Documentation
The documentation of the award procedures contained only in a few cases justifications for the selection of candidates.
