Selection of candidates
In the construction of a motorway ring, bidders were not provided with information on the assessment criteria and the evaluation procedures.
In the case of open procedures for the development and modernisation of waterways and ports, the notices did not indicate how the selection of candidates should be carried out.
In one procedure, all eight participating applicants met the qualification requirements, which exceeded the maximum number of companies to be admitted.
The award committee then carried out a procedure to select the companies.
However, this approach, which was acceptable in principle at the time, should have been cited as one of the criteria in the notice.
Summary findings
Due to the high risk of manipulation in the selection of candidates in non-public procurement procedures, both countries have taken special precautions to prevent undue restrictions on competition.
With the multi-eye principle, the secrecy of the lists of bidders and the sole authority of the contracting authorities to propose the companies to be invited, the German regulations restrict such possibilities of abuse.
In the case of Czech regulations, the newly introduced requirement of the largely unlimited number of bidders in the case of non-public procedures can counteract possible manipulative restrictions.
However, the audit findings have shown that some of these requirements have been insufficiently implemented and that the potential for manipulation for improperly restricting the field of participants has not been sufficiently reduced in these cases.
The contracting authorities should completely eliminate the shortcomings that have been highlighted.
Offer phase
With the announcement of the award or the request for a bid, the bidding phase begins, during which the companies can draw up bids on the basis of the tender documents sent to them.
Applicants can submit their bids until the deadline set by the awarding authority.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
There are no separate EU legal requirements for this phase of the award procedure.
The contracting authorities have to comply with the national regulations, which are intended to counteract the possibilities of manipulation that exist during the offer phase.
These are, above all, organisational requirements and controls.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The procurement documents on the basis of which the companies are to draw up their bids are, in principle, only to be sent by the contracting authority.
Freelancers involved in the procurement process are not allowed to carry out this task.
The contracting authority must ensure that all applicants receive the same information during the tender phase.
In the event of ambiguities in the tender documents or other questions relating to the tender, only the contracting authority may provide information to the applicants.
Freelancers commissioned with the preparation of the award documents are not allowed to provide information.
During the entire offer period, it is necessary to avoid contact between the assigned freelancers as well as the applicants.
Freelancers must not be allowed to become a hub of the award procedure, through which contacts can be established with anti-competitive consequences.
Offers sent by post or directly must be submitted in a sealed envelope.
Electronically transmitted offers have a technical encryption.
Diverging rules
In Germany, the contracting authority can also commission external service companies to print and send the tender documents, whose employees are required to keep the tenders confidential and to fulfil the contractual obligations conscientiously.
The offers received must be marked with an entry stamp in Germany and sent directly, immediately and unopened to a staff member responsible for custody.
This employee may not be involved in the award.
The offers received must be kept under wraps until the opening date.
In the Czech Republic, the tenders received are marked with a file number.
The contracting authority records the offer data, including order numbers, as well as the creation and entry details in a protocol.
The custody of the offers is not specified in the Czech Republic.
