Opening of tenders
Opening of tenders
During the opening date, the previously closed offers will be opened and their contents will be read out and thus made known.
From the opening date, bidders are bound by their bids until the deadline set by the awarding authority.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
There are no separate EU regulations for the opening of tenders.
However, the national regulations on the prevention of corruption contain extensive provisions for the protection of bids and competition for this highly sensitive phase of the award procedure.
The multi-eye principle as well as the transparency and comprehensibility of the offer opening are intended to prevent manipulations and changes in the submitted offers.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The opening date is to be carried out by several persons to be appointed by the contracting authority.
The multi-eye principle is intended to prevent individuals from being able to manipulate the offers uncontrollably when opening up the offers.
In most procurement procedures, bidders can participate in the opening date.
Only offers which were submitted to the head of the negotiations when the first offer was opened are permitted for opening.
Late bids may in principle no longer be taken into account.
In order to ensure the transparency of the opening date, the actions taken and the results of the opening of the bid must be recorded in a protocol, including the names of the bidders and the bid prices.
The protocol must be read out and signed by the negotiators.
It can also be signed by the bidders present.
Diverging rules
In the Czech Republic, a committee is carrying out the opening of tenders.
Freelancers can also play a part in this.
The committee can also be tasked with further stages of the award procedure, such as valuing the bids.
In Germany, a negotiator and a secretary open the offer.
The head of the negotiations must be an official of the vacancy.
The head of the negotiations and, in the case of construction contracts, the secretary should not be involved in the processing of the procurement documents, as well as in the award and contract execution.
According to the German regulations, the minutes of the opening date include not only the offer prices, but also details of discounts and special features, such as damaged or delayed offers.
In the Czech Republic, in addition to the offer price, only the language of the offer and the signature authority of the applicant are recorded.
The German regulations stipulate that the open offers must be marked in all parts in such a way that subsequent changes and additions are prevented.
The offers are usually marked by perforations with the date of the opening date. They are to be kept secret after the opening date and may only be made available to the persons directly responsible for the processing.
Czech regulations do not exist.
In the case of an award procedure in the Czech Republic, if only an offer is received, it must not be opened and must be returned unvalued.
There is no such regulation in Germany. If there is only one offer, it must be opened and then evaluated.
