Examination and evaluation of the offers
Examination and evaluation of the offers The client has to examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.
He has to determine the offer for the award of the contract, which is best suited to the requirements according to the given award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
The EU's requirements provide for a multi-step process:
First of all, there is the suitability of the bidders.
Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
In principle, companies that have been convicted of bribery or fraud, for example, must be excluded from participating in the award procedure.
The bids of the non-excluded bidders must be examined in arithmetical, technical and economic terms and assessed on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. Offers with unusually low prices have to be examined in particular by the client.
The examination and evaluation of the tenders is a particularly tamper-prone phase of the award procedure.
For example, bidders can be unfairly excluded or bids that do not meet the requirements can be left in competition.
By favouring or disadvantaging bidders, the result of the valuation can be impermissibly impaired and thus the establishment of the economically most advantageous tender can be prevented.
The contracting authority therefore has to take special precautions to ensure that the persons in charge of the examination and evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure the transparency and comprehensibility of the procedure and the decisions taken.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
In line with EU requirements, bids in both countries must be examined and evaluated in a multi-stage process.
The requirements for the certificates of suitability of the companies to be submitted, as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting are laid down in the announcements or in the award documents and can no longer be changed during the procedure.
After the examination of the bidder's suitability, the eligibility criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the bids.
The rating has to be limited to the award criteria.
The submitted bids must first be formally examined as soon as possible in order to determine whether they are complete and whether they contain, for example, anomalies that could indicate possible intentions of manipulation.
If bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their bids, they must be informed of this without delay.
If the valuation of the bids results in a price that appears to be unreasonably low, the bidder must be given the opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his bid.
The decisions taken during the examination and evaluation of the offers are to be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Diverging rules
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to persons directly responsible for the processing.
The review of the bids and the calculation of the bids may only be carried out by the contracting authority.
It only has to employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of further examination and evaluation tasks is not specified.
If freelancers are tasked with the examination and evaluation, they have to treat the offers confidentially.
They can only make proposals for the decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.
In the Czech Republic, award committees are to be set up to examine and evaluate the tenders.
The committees draw up evaluation reports with proposals for awarding contracts.
At the end of the day, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the award of contracts.
If evidence or declarations required for the submission of bids in Germany are only incompletely submitted, the contracting authority must give the bidders the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the deadline, the offer is excluded from the valuation.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the contracting authority whether it gives bidders the opportunity to complete missing evidence or explanations.
If a bidder fails to do so, he must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers are to be examined.
If, on the basis of the price structure of the offer, there are indications that prices for partial services are too low or too high, the bidder must be asked to remove these ambiguities.
If he fails to do so and the contracting authority can provide proof of a mixed calculation of the prices, this offer shall be excluded.
The aim is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant changes in the volume of partial services when calculating their bid, which can lead to significant increases in the cost of construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the appropriateness of the prices for partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
Bids with unreasonably high or low prices may not be subject to a surcharge in Germany.
If one or more bids fall short of the relevant price determination of the client or the bid amounts of the other bidders by 10% or more, the bidders have to prove the correct calculation of their bids.
If they are unable to do so, the contracting authority may exclude the bids in question.
In the Czech Republic, the tender can be cancelled after the cost-effectiveness test, if only tenders with unfathomable low prices are available.
Contrary to German public procurement law, for this reason, the contract cannot be refused in the case of bids with prices substantially higher than the client's calculation.
If there are suspicions of anti-competitive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority must immediately report to its specialist supervisory authority at the leading level.
It has to decide on the measures to be taken and whether to inform the anti-trust authority or the public prosecutor.
The leading level of specialist supervision, for example, must also agree to more than 50,000 euros for construction services, if a contract is to be awarded by hand, if a contract is not awarded to the offer with the lowest price, or if the tender is to be cancelled.
There are no such regulations in the Czech Republic.
