BRH
Suitability and evaluation criteria
The vast majority of the audited procurement procedures were in line with the requirements listed.
For some companies proposed by freelancers, the contracting authorities did not check the suitability of the companies themselves.
A grant recipient contracted companies without the required proof of suitability being available in full.
In some cases, it was not clear whether the awarding authority took into account all the award criteria announced in its selection decision or whether it had based its award decision solely on the "price" criterion.
Selection of the persons involved and confidentiality of the offers
Some contracting authorities used non-approved persons to examine the tenders.
For example, freelancers or employees involved in the planning or implementation of a construction project carried out tasks that were only performed by employees of the contracting authority.
The construction services justified this by insufficient staff capacity in the respective areas.
In some cases, the freelancers responsible for the examination of the offers also involved employees who were not obliged to keep the offers confidential and to fulfil the contractual obligations conscientiously.
For the construction services, it was mostly not possible to understand whether the offers for the freelancers were only accessible to the persons directly responsible for the processing.
Review and arithmetical examination of the offers
Some contracting authorities handed over the open tenders to freelancers for further examination, without having first carried out the prescribed review of the tenders and the computational examination itself and docu-mented their results.
In the case of manipulative intentions, third parties could have made changes to the bids without this being comprehensible to the contracting authorities.
In some cases, anomalies or a lack of price or product information were not or only insufficiently marked in the documents examined.
Performance audit
In a sample in a building management department, the cheapest offers in three-quarters of the audited procurement procedures were more than 10% different from the estimated costs previously determined.
One in 20 procurement procedures has been cancelled due to inappropriate bid prices.
Not all bid tests and reconnaissance talks with the bidders were traceable or sufficiently documented.
In many cases, more detailed information was lacking, such as the unit prices of the most important positions.
Often, the deviations were only justified on a flat-rate basis, e.g., by references to changed market prices or increased material costs.
Construction services said it was difficult to identify and prove mixed calculations.
In a call for tenders by an institution under public law, the offer price of the cheapest offer was 66% below the estimated value of these services previously determined.
Further calculations or investigations into the causes of this deviation were not documented.
In a briefing, the contracting authority did not find any evidence of price dumping by the company then commissioned.
This left it unclear whether the estimated value was inflated or the offer price was too low.
Later, the client assessed the contracted company as a "cheap company" that could not keep quality or deadlines.
In another call for tenders, a construction department awarded the contract to an offer whose price was 35% higher than the value of the cost calculation.
She did not rescind the call for tenders, citing the non-material justification that this company could be closed to a reasonable calculation.
Suspicion of irregularities
In the case of an audited construction administration, there were two cases of irregularities, both of which were reported to the specialist supervisor.
In one of the cases, the calculation of two bidders was identical in a tender, so that the contracting authority excluded both bids from the procedure.
In the application of the other regulations, the tests did not give rise to any significant objections.
NKÚ
Aptitude test
For many of the construction projects examined, including higher education, road construction and the extension of the railway network, the contracting authorities did not exclude bidders from the procedure, even though they did not meet the requirements specified in the tender documents or could not prove their suitability to the prescribed extent. On the other hand, in one case, a contracting authority could neither prove nor explain why it had excluded a bidder who had met the requirements.
Scoring
When awarding construction services for a water treatment plant, the contracting authority did not take into account the predetermined assessment criteria in the examination and evaluation of the tenders.
In the case of a construction project for the expansion of the railway network, the contracting authority determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria only at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road maintenance measures, the predetermined criterion of "shortening the construction phase" was misjudged in a procedure.
As a result, the shortening offered was insufficiently taken into account by the second and third-place bidders.
Documentation of the selection of offers
In three procurement procedures in the context of housing subsidies, the contracting authority did not document the criteria it applied and the basis on which it had selected the successful bidder.
When building a motorway, the contracting authority selected the companies for smaller contracts up to 20,000 euros solely on the basis of telephone surveys at prices and delivery terms.
Examinations of this selection were not possible because the interviews were not documented.
Summary findings
The regulations for the examination and evaluation of the offers in both countries correspond to the requirements of the EU.
However, in the case of details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective regulations differ from one another.
In Germany, the process is more regulated than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multi-eye principle and for the protection of offers.
The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the appropriateness of the offered prices has to be examined.
In both countries, in some of the procurement procedures examined, it had to be established that substantial procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of the tenders were not, or were insufficiently, documented.
Without comprehensibility and transparency of the examination and evaluation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are favoured.
A particularly serious defect was the handing over of all offers to third parties, without the contracting authority having previously sufficiently reviewed and documented the offers and thus protected them from possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
If public authorities allow tasks to be performed in the examination and evaluation of bids by third parties, sufficient precautions and an increased control effort are required in order to counter the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the appropriateness of prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the set of instruments and did not sufficiently examine the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, complaints were raised in particular with regard to the aptitude test and the application of the evaluation criteria.
Conclusion of the award procedure
After the examination and values of the tenders, the award procedure is completed by the award of the contract or by the cancellation of the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
The companies have the possibility to examine the intended award for information by electronic means or by fax within 10 days or for other means of communication within 15 days and, if necessary, to initiate a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the end of this information period.
THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank
If a bidder submits a request for review within the information period, a contract can only be concluded after the final decision in the review procedure.
Companies can also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court as part of this review process.
The review procedure is intended to ensure the legal protection of companies and to encourage the contracting authority to observe public procurement law throughout the award procedure.
In order to do this, he has to document the procedure sufficiently.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and review procedures.
In both countries, the contracting authority has to decide on the award of the contract.
However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of proper examination and evaluation of the offers.
The client shall place the order within the announced contract period,
Also because the bidders are no longer bound to their bids after the deadline.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and restricted tenders, the client may in principle not deviate from the content of the offer when concluding the contract.
The unsuccessful bidders must be informed promptly of the award decision and of the reasons for not taking their bids into account.
Procurement procedures may only be cancelled under certain conditions, e.g., if bid prices are inflated or the bids do not meet the requirements of the tender.
Diverging rules
In the Czech Republic, the 10- or 15-day information and waiting period before the award of the contract also applies to construction works that are not to be awarded throughout Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to the area of EU-wide procurement.
In the case of the other procedures in Germany, bidders can only be informed of the award decision after the award has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, an award procedure has to be cancelled if only one bid has been received or only one bid has been evaluated.
In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only one valid offer, provided that it meets the conditions of the tender and is economical.
Key findings of the audit
BRH
In the case of the audited awards, there were only a few complaints at the conclusion of the award procedures.
In some cases, companies received letters of contract for EU-wide contracts before the end of the information period, which may result in the ineffectiveness of the contract.
In individual cases, letters of order also contained content that deviates from the content of the offer, such as changed dates, according to open procedures.
In several cases, the contracting authorities did not comply with the award deadlines.
In the case of an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the contract on the second most favourable offer, since a company with a 50% more favourable offer was no longer prepared to carry out the services at the price originally offered after the contract period had expired.
NKÚ
In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content in the contract.
For some contracts, such as road maintenance works, the construction of a motorway and a bypass, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after the legal deadline.
In the award of construction services for the rehabilitation of former military sites, the contracting authority only forwarded the notification of the award of the contract to all bidders after the expiry of the legal deadline.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU requirements for the conclusion of the award procedure.
The legal protection of under-applicants or bidders increases the toolbox of corruption prevention.
In Czech public procurement law, the scope of legal protection is also extended to contracts below EU thresholds.
In both countries, the deadlines for placing orders have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
In the future, the building authorities should avoid the shortcomings identified when completing their procurement procedures.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The award procedures must be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the justifications of the individual decisions.
In the case of EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made known.
The order data is also recorded in an EU statistics.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention The documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.
Documentation that has been carefully and promptly drawn up will only make it possible to trace the award decisions.
It also serves, in particular, to provide effective legal protection for bidders when awarding contracts above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the obligation to justify procurement decisions in detail significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.
The announcement of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure must be submitted by the contracting authority to the Office for Official Publications of the EU within 48 days.
The Office will publish the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, thus also implementing the transparency requirement.
The contracting authorities also have to collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission via the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the EU Commission draws up an annual EU statistics, through which it can gain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Regulations of the German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed EU requirements on documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Diverging rules
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide awards, there is a publishing obligation only for restricted tenders and for hands-free contracts with a value limit of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without sales tax (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits, as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competitive process receive information on the award of contracts.
Key findings of the audit
BRH
Documentation
A large number of the audited procurement procedures were not fully documented.
The award notes did not contain all the necessary information, such as the justification of product specifications or references to national regulations.
In the case of a procurement procedure, the contracting authority did not justify why it awarded the contract to a company, even though its offer did not include mandatory evidence to be provided.
In a few cases, the documents of the contracting authorities did not contain all the evidence required for the documentation of the award procedure.
Contract award notices
In some EU-wide procurement procedures, the contracting authorities failed to publicise the award of the contracts.
In the case of further procurement procedures, there was no evidence that the contracting authorities had made the contracts awarded known.
Reporting and reporting obligations
The statistical tables inspected contained the required minimum information. They were drawn up and sent on time.
Ex-post transparency
In most cases, the audited construction authorities published the contract data of the completed procurement procedures.
However, a building management company did not publish this data due to a transmission error.
The building authorities only noticed this error after half a year,
So that the contract data of the procurement procedures completed by then have not been published.
NKÚ
Documentation
In the case of construction measures for the organisation of a major sporting event, the documentation of the award procedures showed considerable shortcomings, mainly due to inaccurate information, such as incorrect bid prices in the minutes of the rating commissions.
In addition, some minutes of the opening of bids were not signed.
Contract award notices
For several road construction projects, notices of contracts awarded were only published late or not at all.
Summary findings
The rules on documentation and reporting and reporting obligations are broadly consistent in both countries and implement EU requirements.
The transparency of procurement procedures, including the award of contracts, is thus guaranteed in principle.
The regulations to be applied in the Czech Republic for publication go a little further than the requirements in Germany.
The shortcomings identified in the documentation and in the notices substantially limited the preventive effect of these instruments in the respective procurement procedures.
