The construction authorities should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and contracts and fully comply with their reporting and reporting obligations.
Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two key areas, which in the Czech Republic and Germany are essential for the award of works by public authorities: the application of EU public procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law allow for cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only intended to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to prevent economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of the procurement regulations in both countries, as well as the comparison of these regulations, indicate similarities and differences that may be helpful for both countries in the further development of their public procurement law and its application.
Application of EU public procurement rules
The EU's requirements for the award of construction services have been transposed into national law by both countries.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of construction services and the consideration of the essential requirements of competition, the equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of the procurement procedures.
The building authorities of both countries have, in some cases, subjected these bids to a great deal of additional administrative requirements.
The Czech Republic has to a large extent also transferred the requirements for the construction works to be awarded throughout the EU to its nationally adjustable procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the investigations carried out by the courts of auditors have shown that the construction authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The building authorities in Germany should further improve the quality of their procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the objections raised when implementing the EU requirements.
The tests in the Czech Republic have shown, above all, risks that affect the profitability of the awards.
Incomplete descriptions of services required additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation, and cost assessments were often inadequate, and excessive skill requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, especially in transport buildings.
Corruption prevention
The investigations have not been aimed at uncovering cases of corruption,
It is also because the courts of auditors do not have the necessary instruments to do this.
The courts of auditors can, however, examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of construction services and how these requirements are applied.
When it comes to preventing corruption, the two countries have set different priorities.
The German regulations provide, above all, for a largely unrestricted competition, as well as transparency and controls, as central elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared to their specific requirements.
In some cases, the relevant regulations set out very precisely how the bids to prevent corruption should be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the view of the BRH, in particular, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender is a suitable instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.
Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eye principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures, as well as various organisational measures, are also effective measures to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The BRH therefore sees no need for any fundamental change to the corresponding requirements of the administration in the award of construction services.
The rules on corruption prevention are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have revealed shortcomings in the implementation of some of the benchmarks.
The building authorities should further train their employees on the requirements for the prevention of corruption and make them even more aware of this problem.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building authorities had delegated to freelancers.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.
Therefore, manipulation and corruption-prone tasks should only be transferred to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against undue interference.
NKÚ
The Czech Republic has adopted an anti-corruption strategy at government level, in which public procurement is the most important element.
The Law on Public Procurement and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The tests of the NKÚ took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, since the contracting authorities must justify the cost-effectiveness of the contract awards, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and must properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The NKÚ and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU requirements.
Widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's bids for competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects to enable and promote cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideological potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see the building authorities in their countries as being required to continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to be able to identify the need for action and to initiate appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
A greater division of construction services into lots can also have a positive effect on bid prices, provided that it achieves greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient awarding of contracts by public authorities.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised construction authorities. In the Czech Republic, however, these tasks - with the exception of transport construction projects - are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.
The courts of auditors of both countries have the intention, even after the completion of their joint project, to develop the relevant findings for them and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.
Both courts of auditors are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at international level to the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively combat corruption and to ensure the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
